# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ace-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The **1981 Oakland Athletics season** was the 81st season for the Oakland Athletics franchise, all as members of the American League, and their 14th season in Oakland.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The Athletics finished with an overall record of 64 wins and 45 losses.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] They finished the season with the best record in the American League (and second best in all of baseball; the Cincinnati Reds had the best record in the majors that year going 66-42 but missed the playoffs).
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Due to the infamous 1981 players strike, the league resorted to a split-season format; this new format saw the winners of both halves of the season playing in the first divisional playoff in MLB history.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's qualified by posting the American League West's best record in the first half of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] While they swept the Kansas City Royals in the ALDS, they were themselves swept by the New York Yankees in the ALCS.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The Athletics' 1981 season ranks among the organization's most interesting.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's, only two years removed from a disastrous 54–108 finish, won their first AL West crown since 1975 under second-year manager Billy Martin.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The "Billyball" A's began the season with a then-AL record 11 consecutive wins (this record was later broken by the 1987 Milwaukee Brewers, who raced out to a 13–0 start).
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The squad followed its first loss of the season, a tough 3–2 loss to the Seattle Mariners, with six more victories.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Their 17-1 start (through 18 games) remains unmatched.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's starting rotation (consisting of Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, Mike Norris, and Brian Kingman) received national attention during the torrid start; the unit was collectively featured on the cover of Sports Illustrated's April 27, 1981, edition.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The periodic heroics of Tony Armas and Rickey Henderson also drew notice.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The Athletics, however, slumped badly following the 17–1 start.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] While they regained some of their swagger during the season's second half, they ultimately played .500 baseball for the rest of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Even still, the A's won the AL West's first half with a 37–23 mark; they also led the division in total wins despite losing the second half to the Royals.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's swept the Royals in the ALDS 3–0.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's themselves were humbled in the ALCS, as the Yankees outscored Oakland 20–4 in a humiliating three-game rout.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The 1981 ALCS is perhaps best remembered as the purported birthplace of "the wave"; while the phenomenon's origin is disputed, it is most commonly attributed to Krazy George Henderson, who introduced it to the Athletics' crowd during the series' final game.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Despite high expectations, the A's collapsed in 1982.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] A rash of injuries, among other factors, saw the team plummet to an abysmal 68-94 record.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The firing of Billy Martin at seasons' end brought a swift and unceremonious end to the "Billyball" era.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] All told, the A's would have to wait until 1988 for their next postseason appearance.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Only one member of the 1981 team (Rich Bordi) also played on the 1988 team.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Finley's wife sought a divorce and would not accept part of a baseball team in a property settlement.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] With most of his money tied up in the A's or his insurance empire, Finley had to sell the team.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Though Finley found a buyer in businessman Marvin Davis, who would have moved the Athletics to Denver, the tentative deal hit a snag when the Raiders announced their move to Los Angeles.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Oakland and Alameda County officials, not wanting to be held responsible for losing Oakland's status as a big-league city in its own right, refused to let Finley break the lease with the Coliseum.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Finley then looked to local buyers, selling the A's to San Francisco clothing manufacturer Walter A.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Haas, Jr., president of Levi Strauss & Co. prior to the 1981 season.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Haas restored the official name of the club to "Athletics" in 1981, but retained the nickname "A's" for marketing purposes.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] At first, the word "Athletics" was restored only to the club's logo, underneath the much larger stylized-"A" that had come to represent the team since the early days.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Former owner Charlie Finley banned the word "Athletics" from the club's name because he felt that name was too closely associated with former Philadelphia Athletics owner Connie Mack.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] During the Finley era, average home attendance from 1968–1980 was 777,000 per season, with 1,075,518 in 1975 being the highest attendance for a Finley-owned team.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] In marked contrast, during the first year of Haas' ownership, the Athletics drew 1,304,052—in a season shortened by a player strike.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Were it not for the strike, the A's were on a pace to draw over 2.2 million in 1981.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The A's finished with the second-best overall record in baseball, and the best record in the American League.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The Oakland Athletics held spring training at Rendezvous Park in Mesa, Arizona.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Following the team's surprising success in 1980, manager Billy Martin was given the additional title of general manager in 1981.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The team won the division title for the first time since 1975, winning the first half of the split season, then defeating the Royals in the divisional playoffs before losing to the Yankees in the ALCS.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] While the team was successful, it came at a high price, both for the team and for the pitching staff.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Following a season in which the team led the league in complete games with 94—an astonishing number for the time—the Athletics again led the league with 60 complete games out of 109 total games in the strike-shortened season.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] For the second time, the pitching staff completed more than half their total number of games and more than double the number of the team with the second-highest total (The Indians and Tigers each had 33).
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] The workload of the pitchers over the two seasons was blamed by the team's ownership for the team's fall to fifth place in 1982, which led to Martin's firing from both positions.
[src:ace-baseball/1981-oakland-athletics-season] Many of the pitchers suffered injuries, and none of the four main starting pitchers (Rick Langford, Steve McCatty, Mike Norris, Matt Keough) ever duplicated their success of 1980–81.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] The **1993 Atlanta Braves season** was the Braves' 123rd in existence and their 28th since moving to Atlanta.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves were looking to improve on their 98–64 record from 1992 and win the National League pennant for a third consecutive year, and finally win a World Series in the 1990s.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] 1993 was also the last year that the team competed in the National League West, as they would shift to the National League East for 1994.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves did not record a single losing record against any team in the division.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] The 1993 Atlanta Braves are seen as one of the greatest Major League Baseball teams in history.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] Despite their excellent regular season, the Braves' streak of National League pennants ended at two as they fell to the underdog Philadelphia Phillies in six games in the NLCS.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] By a twist of fate, the Braves beat the Pittsburgh Pirates, the Phillies in-state rivals, in back-to-back NLCS series in 1991 and 1992, but in 1993, lost to the Pirates in-state rivals.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] July 20, 1993: At Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, a fire broke out in the skybox/press box area, delaying the start of the scheduled game between the Braves and the St.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] Incidentally, the Braves' trade for Fred McGriff was completed a few days earlier and McGriff arrived at the stadium that night.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] With the delayed start, McGriff was able to suit up and start the game at first base.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] McGriff helped the Braves erase a 5–0 deficit by hitting a two-run homer in the sixth inning.
[src:ace-baseball/1993-atlanta-braves-season] The Braves went on to win the game, 8–5.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] The **1996 Atlanta Braves season** was the 126th season in the history of the franchise and 31st season in the city of Atlanta.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] They had a regular season record of 96–66 and reached the World Series, where they lost to the underdog New York Yankees in six games, failing to defend their championship in 1995.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Heavily favored and seen as one of the greatest Braves teams in history and despite taking a 2–0 lead, the Braves unexpectedly lost the next 4 games.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] This World Series appearance was their fourth appearance in the last 5 years as a franchise, excluding the strike-abbreviated 1994 season.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Atlanta won its seventh division title (second in the National League East, the other five in the NL West) and its fifth in six years.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] In the previous round, Atlanta completed a miraculous comeback.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Louis three games to one, Atlanta outscored St.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Louis 32–1 in games five through seven to complete the comeback.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] The 1996 season was the Braves' final season at Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium, with Game 5 of the 1996 World Series being the last game played in the stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Atlanta–Fulton County Stadium also served as a venue during the 1996 Summer Olympics held in Atlanta, prompting the Braves to go on an extended road trip as their stadium hosted the baseball competition.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Following the closing ceremonies of the 1996 Summer Paralympics, Centennial Olympic Stadium was reconstructed as planned into Turner Field, which would become the home of the Braves for the next 20 seasons.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] This was also the final season for Ted Turner as the owner of the Braves.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] The team would be acquired (along with TBS) by Time Warner in October 1996, following the World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] Atlanta had an excellent pitching staff, which set an MLB record with 1,245 strikeouts, besting the 1969 Houston Astros.
[src:ace-baseball/1996-atlanta-braves-season] The record was surpassed by 4 teams in 2001.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Philadelphia Phillies' 2011 season was the 129th season in the history of the franchise.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies won their fifth consecutive National League East championship, and also finished with the best record in baseball for the second straight year.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies, at 3–1 odds, were the heavy-favorite to win the World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] However, they were eliminated in the NLDS in five games by the eventual World Series champion St.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] This was the last season that the Phillies made the postseason until 2022, making it the longest active postseason drought in the National League at the time.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The 2011 Phillies were the last team until the 2015 Cardinals to finish the season with at least 100 wins.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies had three pitchers with 6.0 or more Baseball Reference pitching wins above replacement, tying the record for the most such pitchers in a season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The other teams to accomplish this were the 1891 Boston Beaneaters, 1913 Chicago White Sox, 1925 Cincinnati Reds, and 2017 Washington Nationals.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The offseason for the Phillies began on October 23, 2010, when they lost the National League Championship Series to the San Francisco Giants.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Although all coaches were invited to return for the 2011 season, first-base coach Davey Lopes informed the team that he would be leaving because of a salary dispute.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] To replace him, third-base coach Sam Perlozzo was moved to first base, and former Phillies second baseman and Orioles' third-base coach and interim manager Juan Samuel was hired to take over at third base.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On November 16, the Phillies signed reliever José Contreras to a two-year contract after he posted a 3.34 ERA in 2010.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On December 6, right fielder Jayson Werth signed a seven-year contract with the Washington Nationals.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On December 15, the Phillies re-signed Cliff Lee, the starting pitcher whom they had traded to the Seattle Mariners during the previous offseason in order to acquire Roy Halladay.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] With the addition of Lee, Halladay, Cole Hamels, and Roy Oswalt earned the nickname "**The Four Aces**".
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies stormed out of the gate, sweeping the Houston Astros on opening weekend.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Three out of the four aces won their first starts (Hamels lost against the Mets).
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] José Contreras was said to be the new Phillies closer; however, he got injured in late April, and was replaced by Ryan Madson.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Madson continued the year in the closer position.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies finished April with an 18–8 record, the second best in the majors, trailing only the Cleveland Indians, a team whom they traded with throughout the month for the best record in the majors.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On May 9, the Phillies took sole possession of the best record in the majors, a position that they would hold for the rest of the regular season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] May was their second-worst month record-wise (following September)—they did not have many winning or losing streaks.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] However, the Phillies' game against rival New York Mets on May 1 was an unforgettable one, although they lost 2–1 in 14 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Mike Lopresti of *USA Today* said that the Phillies' rivals "was a perfect fit" when the news broke.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies finished May with a 34–22 record.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] June was a very good month for the Phillies.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] In the middle of the month, they went on a seven-game winning streak, taking three of four from the Chicago Cubs, and a four-game sweep of the Florida Marlins.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] They came back to earth, trading several wins and losses over the next week.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] June concluded with the marquee match-up against the Boston Red Sox, a series many predicted to be a World Series preview (as it turned out, neither team made the Fall Classic).
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies dominated, taking two of three, highlighted by Cliff Lee's shutout performance in the first game of the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Lee went 5–0 with a 0.21 ERA in June, which earned him NL Pitcher of the Month.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] In June, Lee had more RBIs than earned runs (2 RBIs and only 1 earned run).
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies finished June with a 52–31 record.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] By the beginning of July, the Phillies were certainly living up to their preseason hype, and were looking to be a definite contender for the World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] July was the best month for the Phillies; they compiled a 17–8 record, and were beginning to run away with the NL East.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On July 11, the Phillies overtook the top spot on ESPN's Power Rankings, a spot they would hold for the remaining 12 weeks of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies sent five players (Roy Halladay, Cliff Lee, Cole Hamels, Plácido Polanco, and Shane Victorino) to the All Star Game.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies finished July with a 69–39 record.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies began August riding a nine-game winning streak, and in time, extended their lead in the NL East to 8.5 games.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] After several months of being injured, Roy Oswalt came back into action in the Phillies, winning his first two starts by a combined score of 16–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Because of Hurricane Irene, the Phillies had to play 33 games in 31 days, from August 29 to September 28.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Along the way, they played three doubleheaders, the last of which came as a result of a rain-out in September.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On August 31, the Phillies reached 40 games over .500—for the first time since their back-to-back 100+ win seasons in 1976 and 1977, in which they went 101–61—with a 3–0 win in Cincinnati against the Reds and improved to 86–46.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Wins during the next two days got them to 42 games over .500 for the first time in franchise history.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] On September 14, the Phillies became the first team to clinch a playoff spot with a 1–0 win in Houston, against Hunter Pence's former team, after acquiring him at the trade deadline.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Three days later, they clinched the NL East title for the fifth consecutive season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] With 102 wins, the Phillies had the best record in baseball for the second year in a row and broke the franchise record for most regular-season wins.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Towards the end of the season, the Phillies had an eight-game losing streak, but even with this streak, they had already clinched the NL East, as well as the best record in the majors.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies ended the season by sweeping the Braves, capped off by a 14-inning win in the last game of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] By winning the final game of the regular season, Phillies Manager Charlie Manuel also became the manager with the most wins in Phillies history.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The win by the Phillies also eliminated the Braves from postseason contention, and allowed the St.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Louis Cardinals to play in the postseason.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies also led the major leagues in attendance for the first time, with 3,680,718 fans (a franchise record), an average of 45,440 per game.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies finished out the season with a sweep of the Atlanta Braves, and in doing so, allowed the St.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Louis Cardinals to clinch the National League wild-card on the last day of the regular season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Having finished with the best record for the second year in a row, the Phillies had home-field advantage for the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Game 1 saw the Cardinals jump out to an early lead, with a three-run homer by Lance Berkman in the top of the 1st, off Phillies ace Roy Halladay.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies bats woke up in the 6th inning, with home runs by Ryan Howard and Raúl Ibañez.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] In addition to the offense waking up, Halladay tamed the Cardinals, retiring 21 straight batters, and the Phillies took game 1, 11–6.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Game 2 featured another Philadelphia ace, Cliff Lee, facing the Cardinals' Chris Carpenter, who would make his first start on three days rest of his career.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies jumped out to a 4-run lead, however, Cliff Lee surrendered 5 runs, as the Cardinals came back, and took game 2, 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The series then went to Busch Stadium in St.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Game 3 featured Cole Hamels taking on Jaime García, both of whom pitched a scoreless game through 6 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] In the 7th inning, the Phillies' pinch-hitter Ben Francisco fired a three-run homer to give the Phillies the lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Cardinals were able to fight back and get 2 runs, but Ryan Madson shut the door, with a 5-out save, to give the Phillies a 2–1 series lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] In Game 4, a matchup between Roy Oswalt and Edwin Jackson, the Phillies again jumped out to an early 2-run lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Cardinals cut the lead in half in the bottom of the first.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] David Freese was the hero of game 4, with a two-run double in the fourth, which gave the Cardinals the lead, and a two-run homer in the sixth.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies were not able to come back, and that sent the series back to Philadelphia tied at two games.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Game 5 featured a marquee pitching matchup, with former Toronto teammates, Roy Halladay and Chris Carpenter facing off.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Again, the Cardinals took an early lead, with Rafael Furcal scoring off a Skip Schumaker double.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] It turned out that was all the Cardinals needed, as they went on to win, 1–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] For the Cardinals, it added to their thus-far improbable season, and advanced to the NLCS for the first time since winning the 2006 World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] First baseman Ryan Howard suffered a torn Achilles tendon, that would forced him to miss some time for the 2012 season.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Vance Worley was named by *Baseball America* as one of the five starting pitchers on its All-Rookie Team.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Roy Halladay was named the Sportsperson of the Year by the *Philadelphia Daily News* for the second consecutive year.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Jimmy Rollins (shortstop) and Roy Halladay (one of three starting pitchers) were named to the *MLB Insiders Club Magazine* All-Postseason Team.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Shane Victorino received the Branch Rickey Award for his exceptional community service.
[src:ace-baseball/2011-philadelphia-phillies-season] Retired general manager Pat Gillick was inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The **2025 Los Angeles Dodgers season** was the 136th season for the Los Angeles Dodgers franchise in Major League Baseball (MLB), their 68th season in Los Angeles, California, and their 64th season playing their home games at Dodger Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] For the second year in a row, the Dodgers began the season outside of America, this time in Tokyo, Japan for the Tokyo Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They became the first defending World Series champion to begin their season 8–0, besting the previous record held by the 1933 Yankees, who started their season 7–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Dodgers clinched their 13th straight post-season appearance on September 19, extending the longest streak in franchise history.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On September 25, they clinched the National League West title for the fourth straight season and 12th time the last 13 years.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On September 18, three-time Cy Young winner and former MVP Clayton Kershaw announced his retirement at the conclusion of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] As the third seed, the Dodgers opened the playoffs in the Wild Card Series against the sixth seed, Cincinnati Reds.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They swept the Reds in two games to advance to the NLDS.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They then defeated the Philadelphia Phillies in four games and advanced to the National League Championship Series for the second year in a row.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They swept the Milwaukee Brewers in four games to win their second straight NLCS and the fifth in nine years (2017–2018, 2020, 2024–2025), in a series defined by their starting pitching dominance.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They defeated the Blue Jays in the World Series in seven games to become the first franchise to repeat as World Series champions since the 1998–2000 New York Yankees.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Dodgers were just the ninth team to win Games 6 and 7 on the road in a World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] In Game 7, they were the first team in MLB history to stage a comeback on the road in the ninth inning of a winner-take-all World Series game, ultimately winning in 11 innings by a score of 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] Unlike the previous season, the Dodgers did not hold home-advantage for any of the last three rounds.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Los Angeles Dodgers drew an average home attendance of 49,536, the highest of all MLB teams.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The team also passed 4 million in home attendance for the first time in franchise history.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On October 31, 2024, the day after the 2024 World Series ended, six Dodgers players became free agents.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] They included pitchers Walker Buehler, Jack Flaherty, Joe Kelly and Blake Treinen, outfielder Teoscar Hernández and utility player Kiké Hernández.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] Pitcher Daniel Hudson and outfielder Kevin Kiermaier also announced their retirements after the World Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 4, pitcher Clayton Kershaw declined the player option on his contract, making him a free agent.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 14, the Dodgers outrighted pitcher Connor Brogdon to the minors and removed him from the 40-man roster.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 22, the Dodgers non-tendered pitchers Brent Honeywell Jr. and Zach Logue, making them free agents.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 3, they designated catcher Diego Cartaya for assignment, removing him from the roster.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 6, the Dodgers traded second baseman Gavin Lux to the Cincinnati Reds in exchange for minor league outfielder Mike Sirota and a competitive balance pick in the 2025 MLB draft.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 30, pitcher Ryan Brasier was designated for assignment in order to clear a spot on the 40-man roster.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 10, it was announced that first base coach Clayton McCullough would leave the team to become the Manager of the Miami Marlins.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 22, they hired Chris Woodward, who had been the third base coach for the Dodgers from 2016 to 2018 before leaving to manage the Texas Rangers, to replace McCullough as the first base coach.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Dodgers also announced that Vice President of Player Performance Brandon McDaniel would be joining the major league coaching staff in a new role as Major League Development Integration Coach.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] After the death of Dodger legend and longtime Spanish language broadcaster Fernando Valenzuela at the end of the 2024 season, the Dodgers hired former player Luis Cruz to join the Spanish language broadcast team for 2025 as an analyst.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 19, the Dodgers purchased the contract of left handed pitcher Jack Dreyer from the Triple–A Oklahoma City Comets and added him to the 40-man roster.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On November 30, they signed left-handed pitcher Blake Snell to a five-year, $182 million contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On December 10, they signed outfielder Michael Conforto to a one-year, $17 million contract and re-signed reliever Blake Treinen on a two-year, $22 million contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 3, they re-signed Teoscar Hernández to a three-year, $66 million contract and signed South Korean shortstop Hyeseong Kim to a three-year, $12.5 million contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 22, the Dodgers signed Japanese pitcher Roki Sasaki of the Chiba Lotte Marines to a $6.5 million signing bonus as an international free agent.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The following day, they signed pitcher Tanner Scott to a four-year, $72 million, contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On January 30, they signed relief pitcher Kirby Yates to a one-year, $13 million, contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On February 11, utility player Kiké Hernández re-signed with the Dodgers on a one-year contract.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] Two days later, the Dodgers also re-signed Clayton Kershaw, on a one-year deal, returning him to the roster for an 18th season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Dodgers began spring training on February 10, 2025, when pitchers and catchers reported to Camelback Ranch in Glendale, Arizona with the first full squad workout on February 15 and the first Cactus League game on February 20.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] During this time, they also re-signed manager Dave Roberts to a new four-year contract extension for $8 million per year, a new record for average annual value for a Major League manager.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The deal would keep him under contract through the 2029 season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] On March 11, the Dodgers optioned infielder Hyeseong Kim to the minors after his bat was unable to adjust to major league pitching in spring training and also revealed that Dustin May had won the fifth starter job to open the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] The Dodgers ended their Cactus League schedule on March 11 before flying to Japan to play two exhibition games (against the Hanshin Tigers and Yomiuri Giants of Nippon Professional Baseball) prior to beginning the season with the MLB Tokyo Series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p01] Afterwards, they played the Los Angeles Angels in three Freeway Series exhibitions before resuming the regular season on March 27.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p02] Updated with the results of all games through September 28, 2025.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers opened their season on March 18 against the Chicago Cubs at the Tokyo Dome in Japan as part of the MLB Tokyo Series, the second straight year they had started overseas after playing in Seoul, South Korea to start the 2024 season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yoshinobu Yamamoto made the start in his home country, facing Shota Imanaga, the first opening day matchup between two Japanese pitchers in MLB history.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto allowed only one run on three hits in five innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Shohei Ohtani had two hits, including a double, and scored two runs as the Dodgers started the season with a 4–1 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Roki Sasaki made his major league debut, allowing one run in three innings, while walking five batters.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani, Kiké Hernández, and Tommy Edman homered, and the Dodgers finished the series with a 6–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers returned to Dodger Stadium and began the rest of the schedule on March 27 with a three-game series against the Detroit Tigers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Blake Snell started the home opener, allowing two runs in five innings of work, while the Dodgers hit three more home runs in a 5–4 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Yamamoto struck out 10 batters in five innings, while allowing two solo home runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Mookie Betts hit two home runs, including a walk-off in the 10th inning as the Dodgers won again, 8–5.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Sasaki again struggled in his second start of the season, on March 29, allowing three hits while walking four batters in only 1⁄2 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers hit three more home runs en route to sweeping the Tigers with a 7–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] They played the Atlanta Braves in the next series, and Tyler Glasnow began his season by pitching by pitching five shutout innings while striking out eight in the Dodgers 6–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers' six-game winning streak to start the season matched their best mark since moving to Los Angeles in 1958, joining the 1981 season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Dustin May made his first start since the middle of the 2023 season, after recovering from multiple surgeries, and only allowed one hit while striking out six in five innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers matched the 1933 New York Yankees as the only returning champions to start the season with seven wins.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Blake Snell struggled in his second start, walking four and allowing five runs in four innings, aided by three Dodger errors.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers came back and Max Muncy tied the game in the eighth with a two-run double and then Shohei Ohtani won it with a walk-off home run in the ninth to keep the streak alive.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The first road trip of the season began on April 4 at Citizens Bank Park against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yoshinobu Yamamoto again pitched well in his third start, allowing only one unearned run in six innings but the Dodgers lost their first game of the season, 3–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Roki Sasaki improved in his third start of the season the next day, walking only two in four innings while allowing only one run and striking out four.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Home runs by Kiké Hernández and Michael Conforto helped the Dodgers to a 3–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the series, Tyler Glasnow walked five batters and left the bases loaded in the third which led to a Nick Castellanos grand-slam home run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers came back, thanks to Teoscar Hernández, who hit two home runs, a double, and drove in five runs himself.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Phillies won the game 8–7, scoring the winning run on a RBI single by Bryson Stott in the seventh inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers next series was at Nationals Park against the Washington Nationals.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Dustin May got the start in the opener, allowing only one earned run in six innings, while Ohtani fell a double short of the cycle.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers lost their second game in a row when James Wood hit a two-run home run in the seventh inning as the Nationals won the game 6–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Justin Wrobleski was called up from the minors to make a spot start and he was bad, allowing eight runs on eight hits, including two home runs by Wood, in five innings, as the Dodgers losing streak continued with a 8–2 loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Landon Knack made a sport start also, the following day, giving up five runs on four hits and four walks in only 2+1⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers, thanks to homers by Teoscar Hernández and Andy Pages, came back to win 6–5 to end the losing streak and finish the road trip.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers returned home on April 11 to play the Chicago Cubs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto struck out nine while only allowing two hits and one walk in six scoreless innings, while a three-run home run from Tommy Edman provided all the scoring in a 3–0 win, their 10th straight at home.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Sasaki managed to get through five innings in his next start, while allowing only one run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers offense could manage nothing against Cubs starter Ben Brown, who shut them down in six innings while the Cubs teed off on Dodgers relievers Ben Casparius and Luis García, and handed the Dodgers their worst home shutout loss in franchise history, 16–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Cubs handed the Dodgers their third straight series loss with a 4–2 win in the finale.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Pete Crow-Armstrong had two homers and a triple in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The following series was against the Colorado Rockies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Dustin May struck out seven while only allowing one run on three hits in six innings of the opener.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Mookie Betts and Ohtani each homered in the game, while producing five hits between them in a 5–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Will Smith had two hits, a homerun and drove in three runs and Edman had four hits in five at-bats as the Dodgers won 6–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the homestand, the Dodgers scored seven runs in the first inning, which included home runs by Ohtani and Freddie Freeman.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, Michael Toglia hit a grand slam homer off fill-in starter Bobby Miller in the third inning to make the game close before the Dodgers held-on to win 8–7 and complete the sweep of the Rockies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto had another strong start in the opener of the next road trip, at Globe Life Field against the Texas Rangers, pitching seven shutout innings with 10 strikeouts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers got one run, a solo home run in the first by Edman, off Jacob deGrom, who pitched seven innings for the Rangers, before adding two more against the bullpen for a 3–0 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Sasaki allowed two runs in six innings and the Dodgers, thanks to a Freeman home run took a 3–2 lead into the ninth inning, only to lose the game on a two-run walk-off home run by Adolis García.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, the Dodgers could only manage two hits in seven innings against Tyler Mahle but their pitchers matched him with scoreless innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Will Smith scored the only run of the game on a sacrifice fly by Freeman in the eighth inning for a 1–0 victory and a series win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Next up was a two-game series against the Cubs at Wrigley Field on April 22 and 23.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Edman hit a three-run home run in the top of the first to put the Dodgers ahead early, but May struggled and allowed the Cubs to get five back in the bottom of the inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers used a five run inning of their own in the seventh to take a 10–7 lead only to blow it when Kyle Tucker hit a two-run homer in the eighth and Miguel Amaya hit a game-tying home run in the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ian Happ drove in the winning run in the 10th inning as the Cubs took the game 11–10.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Cubs won again the next day, 7–6, with a three-run home run by Pete Crow-Armstrong in the fifth inning putting them ahead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Back home on April 25 to play the Pittsburgh Pirates, the Dodgers continued to struggle, and were shut out by Paul Skenes and the Pirates, 3–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Ohtani had three hits, including two doubles, and both Teoscar Hernández and Kiké Hernández homered as the Dodgers won 8–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] They won again the next day, 9–2, to win the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Andy Pages had four hits, including a home run, in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Miami Marlins came to town next for a three-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers got out to a 5–0 lead, which included a Teoscar Hernández two-run home run in the fifth, only for the Marlins to tie the game with a pinch-hit grand slam home run by Dane Myers in the sixth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It remained tied until the 10th inning when the Marlins took the lead in the top of the inning, only for the Dodgers to walk it off, 7–6, when Tommy Edman drove in Pages and Michael Conforto with a single.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, Teoscar Hernández had four hits and four RBI, Ohtani and Pages homered and the Dodgers routed the Marlins, 15–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Tony Gonsolin came off the injured list on April 30 and made his first start for the Dodgers since August of the 2023 season, allowing three runs in six innings with nine strikeouts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers completed the sweep of the Marlins with a 12–7 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yoshinobu Yamamoto allowed only one hit in six scoreless innings as the Dodgers began a three-game series against the Atlanta Braves with a 2–1 victory at Truist Park.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The following day, Roki Sasaki picked up his first major league win as the Dodgers won 10–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Shohei Ohtani and Freddie Freeman each had three hits, including a home run, in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Austin Riley had two home runs as the Braves took the series finale, 4–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers next series was against the Miami Marlins at loanDepot Park.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman and Ohtani each homered again the next day as they won the game 7–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] They homered again for the third straight day as Tony Gonsolin struck out eight in five innings, while allowing two runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Marlins came back to tie the game and won it, 5–4, on a bases-loaded walk-off hit by Jesús Sánchez in the 10th inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, a three-run triple by Freeman led to the Dodgers scoring six runs in the seventh to blow open the game and win 10–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Gabriel Moreno hit a grand-slam home run in the fourth as the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Dodgers, 5–3, in the opener of a four-game series at Chase Field on May 8.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next game had several high scoring innings, with the Diamondbacks scoring three in the first, the Dodgers getting five in the third, the Diamondbacks responding with a four run fifth and then the Dodgers getting six runs in the ninth to win 14–11.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] A three-run home run by Ohtani was the deciding factor.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The following day, the Dodgers were shut out by Corbin Burnes and lost 3–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman had four hits (including two doubles and a home run) and drove in four runs in the Dodgers 8–1 win in the series finale.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers returned home on May 13 to play the Athletics.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Athletics hit five home runs (including two by Jacob Wilson) in an 11–1 rout of the Dodgers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, the Dodgers hit four home runs of their own in a 9–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the series, the Dodgers hit another five home runs, including two by Ohtani, and blew out the Athletics, 19–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next series was against the Los Angeles Angels, who beat the Dodgers, 6–2, in the opener.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers hit into a franchise record five double plays in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Andy Pages and Kiké Hernández homered but the Angels Logan O'Hoppe drove in five RBIs, including a three run homer as part of a five run seventh as they won 11–9.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Angels proceeded to sweep the Dodgers with a 6–4 win in the series finale.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yusei Kikuchi struck out seven and only allowed one run on three hits in 5+2⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Mookie Betts hit two home runs in the first game of a three-game series against the Diamondbacks but the Dodgers lost 9–5, extending the losing streak to a season high four games.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game, Yamamoto only gave up one hit in seven innings and the Dodgers took a 1–0 lead into the top of the ninth only for the Diamondbacks to tie it on a solo homer by Gabriel Moreno.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Corbin Carroll hit a two-run home run in the 10th to give Arizona the lead, but the Dodgers came back and won the game, 4–3, with a sacrifice fly from Max Muncy in the bottom of the inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Dustin May struck out eight batters in six innings as the Dodgers won, 3–1, thanks to a 3-run homer from Teoscar Hernández.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On May 23, the Dodgers traveled to Citi Field to face the New York Mets in a 2024 National League Championship Series rematch.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] After a one-hour, thirty-eight-minute rain delay, the Dodgers took a 5–2 lead thanks to RBIs from Will Smith, Teoscar Hernández, Max Muncy, and Andy Pages.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Mets scored three runs off Tanner Scott in the bottom of the ninth to send the game to extra innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ultimately, the Dodgers won, 7–5, thanks to a Hernández RBI and a Pages sacrifice fly in the top of the 13th inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, Brett Baty and Juan Soto had five hits and drove in four runs combined while David Peterson struck out seven in 7+2⁄3 innings and the Mets won, 5–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Mets took the series by taking the final game, 3–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Kodai Senga struck out five in 5+1⁄3 innings, and Pete Alonso's two-run home run in the first inning gave the Mets the lead they never relinquished.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers next began a three-game series with the Cleveland Guardians at Progressive Field with a Memorial Day game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto struck out seven in six innings, while allowing only two runs on three hits.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani and Smith homered as the Dodgers won, 7–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers hit three home runs as part of their 9–5 win in the next game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers took a 4–2 lead into the eighth inning in the series finale, only for the Guardians to score five runs in the inning, which included a three-run home run by Angel Martínez, for a 7–4 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On May 30, the New York Yankees visited Dodger Stadium for a 2024 World Series rematch.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani hit two home runs and Pages recorded three RBIs as the Dodgers recovered from a three-run deficit with four runs in the sixth inning for an 8–5 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The following day, Landon Knack allowed only one run in six innings while the Dodgers jumped on the Yankees early and won 18–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Muncy hit two three-run home runs, Tommy Edman and Hyeseong Kim each had four hits, while Kim, Pages, and Dalton Rushing also homered.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was the most runs ever scored by a National League team against the Yankees in a game, regular season, or postseason.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Yoshinobu Yamamoto struggled, giving up seven hits and allowing four runs, including one on a wild pitch.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers hit three home runs, but it was not enough and they lost, 7–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On June 2, the New York Mets came to Dodger Stadium for a four-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Dustin May struck out five batters in six innings, and a home run and a sacrifice fly from Shohei Ohtani sent the game into extra innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, Tanner Scott allowed two additional runs and the Dodgers lost, 4–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game, Max Muncy homered twice while committing two errors, which led to two runs scoring.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ultimately, the Dodgers won the game, 6–5, on a walk-off double by Freddie Freeman in the bottom of the tenth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the third game of the series, Tony Gonsolin threw six strikeouts in five innings, but Kiké Hernández committed an error, leading to three runs scoring in the first inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers got only three hits off Mets starter Griffin Canning and lost, 6–1, after allowing a three-run home run to Pete Alonso in the eighth inning, his second of the day.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the series and the homestand, the Mets jumped out to a 4–0 lead in the third thanks to three home runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers got three back in the bottom of the inning, and then scored three more in the eighth to win the game, 6–5, and split the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Pedro Pagés homered in the second inning to give the Cardinals a 2–0 lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Sonny Gray allowed eight hits to the Dodgers in his 6+1⁄3 innings but he and three relievers kept the Dodgers scoreless and the Cardinals won 5–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Yamamoto struck out nine in six shutout innings while only giving up four hits.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers lost, 2–1, on a walk-off RBI single from Nolan Arenado.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers avoided being swept by winning the series finale, 7–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Clayton Kershaw struck out seven in five innings, while allowing only one run, to pick up his first win of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers traveled to Petco Park on June 9 to face the San Diego Padres.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The game was tied at six runs after nine innings, and the Dodgers won, 8–7, thanks to RBIs from Andy Pages and Tommy Edman in the tenth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Matt Sauer gave up 13 hits and allowed nine runs in a 11–1 defeat.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers only managed to get three hits off Padres starter Dylan Cease.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers wrapped up the series with a 5–2 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ben Casparius allowed one run in four innings while making a spot start, and the Dodgers took the lead with a three-run home run by Teoscar Hernández in the fifth inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On June 13, the San Francisco Giants came to Dodger Stadium for a three-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto gave up six hits and allowed five runs, including a grand slam to Casey Schmitt, in 4+2⁄3 innings and the Dodgers lost, 6–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Kershaw struck out five and only allowed three hits in seven scoreless innings, Ohtani homered twice and Teoscar Hernández and Miguel Rojas also hit home runs in a 11–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani had three hits and Pages drove in four of the runs, three of them on a home run in the bottom of the fifth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani made his first pitching appearance for the Dodgers, and first since the 2023 season, pitching one inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] He also had two hits and two RBIs as a batter.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers scored five runs in the fourth inning, leading to a 6–3 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Pages had four hits and three RBIs, including two solo home runs, and Will Smith also homered.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the third game, Emmet Sheehan struck out six while allowing three hits and one run in his first start since 2023.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] A Pages' sacrifice fly and a Dalton Rushing RBI double in the fifth gave the Dodgers a 3–1 lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Padres tied the game at three in the top of the ninth as a result of a throwing error from Muncy and a RBI double by Xander Bogaerts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Smith hit a pinch-hit walk-off home run in the bottom of the ninth for a 4–3 Dodgers victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was the third pinch-hit walk-off of his career, breaking a tie with Rick Monday for the most in franchise history.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Yamamoto gave up seven hits and allowed three runs, including a home run to Bogaerts, in a 5–3 defeat.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers scored runs off an error and a wild pitch in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Eight batters were hit in the four-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Manager Dave Roberts was suspended for the opening game of a three-game series against the Washington Nationals as a result of his actions in the previous game against the Padres.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Rojas hit a double and a two-run home run, Ohtani, Betts and Pages each drove in runs and the Dodgers held on for a 6–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Pages, Smith, and Teoscar Hernández all homered.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers allowed five home runs, including two to Nathaniel Lowe, in a 7–2 loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, the Nationals jumped out to a lead thanks to a three-run home run by Lowe in the third inning only for the Dodgers to score four runs in the sixth and seven runs in the seventh en route to a 13–7 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Muncy had two home runs, including a grand slam, and drove in seven runs while Ohtani had a homer and triple and drove in five runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On June 24, the Dodgers traveled to Coors Field to face the Colorado Rockies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Justin Wrobleski struck out seven while only allowing two runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani and Michael Conforto homered, and Teoscar Hernández drove in two runs in a 9–7 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Yamamoto struck out six and only allowed one hit in five scoreless innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Muncy drove in six runs, including a grand slam, following a lengthy rain delay, and the Dodgers won, 8–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers finished off the series with a 3–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Kershaw struck out five in six innings, and Ohtani homered in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani and Muncy both homered again in the following game, the opener of a three-game series against the Kansas City Royals at Kauffman Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Casparius struggled, giving up eight hits and allowing six runs, including a three-run home run to Vinnie Pasquantino in four innings as the Royals won the game 9–5.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers won the last game of the series, 5–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Wrobleski struck out six in six innings as Kiké Hernández and Smith hit home runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yoshinobu Yamamoto struck out eight batters in seven innings and only allowed one run in the first game of a three-game series against the Chicago White Sox at Dodger Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Andy Pages and Michael Conforto each scored two runs and Shohei Ohtani homered in a 6–1 Dodgers victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On July 2, Clayton Kershaw struck out three batters in six innings to reach 3,000 career strikeouts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] He became the 20th pitcher and fourth left handed pitcher in MLB history to reach that mark as well as the third to do so while spending his entire career with one team.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers trailed by two going into the ninth and won the game by scoring three runs in the inning, with Freddie Freeman walking it off with an RBI single to win 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers completed the series sweep with a 6–2 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman drove in three runs and Mookie Betts and Conforto each hit a home run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Dustin May pitched five perfect innings and finished with four hits and two runs allowed in seven innings while striking out nine.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next series was against the Houston Astros.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ben Casparius had a poor performance, giving up nine hits and allowing six runs in three innings on the Fourth of July.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Noah Davis allowed an additional 10 runs in 1+1⁄3 innings as the Dodgers were blown out, 18–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was the biggest blowout loss in the history of Dodger Stadium and the Dodgers overall worst loss since the 2001 season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The 10 runs given up in the sixth inning was the highest number in one inning since the St.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Louis Cardinals scored 11 in the third inning against them on April 23, 1999.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Astros won again in the next game, 6–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Zack Short drove in three runs in the third with a double off Justin Wrobleski, who gave up seven hits and allowed four runs in 4+2⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Emmet Sheehan allowed only one run in five innings but the Astros finished off a series sweep with a 5–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was the first time the Dodgers had been swept by the Astros in Los Angeles since 2008.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers went back on the road on July 7 to play the Milwaukee Brewers at American Family Field.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto had the worst start of his career, allowing five runs on four hits and two walks while recording only two outs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] A three-run home run by Andrew Vaughn was the key and the Brewers won a blow out, 9–1, extending the Dodgers' losing streak to four games.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani led off the next game with a home run, but the Dodgers could only get four hits against Brewers starter Jacob Misiorowski, who struck out 12 in six innings, as the Brewers won 3–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Tyler Glasnow returned from a long stint on the injured list to start the series finale, allowing only one unearned run in five innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers took a 2–1 lead into the ninth only for the Brewers to tie the game and then win it, 3–2, in extra innings on a walk-off hit by Jackson Chourio to extend the Dodgers losing streak to six games, for the first time since April of 2019.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next road series was against the San Francisco Giants at Oracle Park.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] May gave up five hits and allowed seven runs in 4+2⁄3 innings, and a Teoscar Hernández RBI double and Conforto home run reduced the deficit to one run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, Will Smith ground into double play in the ninth inning and the Dodgers lost, 8–7.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers snapped the losing streak on July 12 with a 2–1 victory over the Giants.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani pitched three shutout innings and Sheehan allowed only the one run in 4+1⁄3 innings while Conforto had three hits and scored both runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers finished off the series and headed into the all-star break with a 5–2 win in 11 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto struck out seven in seven scoreless innings but the Giants tied the game with a two-run home run by Luis Matos in the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, Freeman, Teoscar Hernández and Pages each drove in runs in the 11th.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers had five players selected to the 2025 Major League Baseball All-Star Game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani started at designated hitter, Smith at catcher and Freeman at first base.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto was selected as a reserve and Kershaw was added as a legends pick.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The season resumed on July 18 at home against the Brewers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Glasnow struck out six in six innings and allowed only one run, on an RBI double by Caleb Durbin in the fifth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Durbin also homered in the seventh off reliver Kirby Yates and the Brewers won the game 2–0 as the Dodgers managed only three hits off Quinn Priester and three relievers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers then lost their fifth straight game to the Brewers the following day, 8–7, despite hitting three home runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the finale, the Dodgers took a 3–0 lead after a two-run homer by Ohtani in the third but the Brewers scored three runs in the fourth and again in the sixth and swept the season series with a 6–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers committed three errors in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Minnesota Twins came to town for the next series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Will Smith hit two home runs, and Ohtani and Pages also went deep as the Dodgers won 5–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] James Outman robbed a potential game-tying home run from Carlos Correa to end the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani became the first pitcher to allow a home run and hit a home run in the first inning of a game since Randy Lerch of the 1979 Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, the Twins took an early three run lead, the Dodgers tied the game on a three-run home run by Pages in the fourth only for the Twins to score three runs in each of the sixth and seventh innings en route to a 10–7 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Glasnow allowed only one run (a solo home run by Royce Lewis) in seven innings, while striking out 12.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani hit a home run in the first inning, the fifth consecutive game he had homered in, tying the franchise record.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers won, 4–3, on a two-run walk-off hit by Freeman in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On July 25, the Dodgers went on the road to Fenway Park to play a three-game series with the Boston Red Sox.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Teoscar Hernández hit a two-run home run in the eighth inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game, Red Sox starter Garrett Crochet struck out 10 and only allowed two runs in six innings and the Dodgers lost 4–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series finale, Conforto had three hits with two doubles and a home run but the Dodgers stranded 13 runners on base in a 4–3 loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] A two-run homer by Alex Bregman in the fifth counted for the deciding runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Next up for the Dodgers was a three-game series at Great American Ball Park against the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto struck out nine while allowing one run on four hits in seven innings and Betts had two hits and scored three runs in a 5–2 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers took the next game as well, 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Tommy Edman started the scoring with a two-run homer in the second and then Will Smith drove in the winning run with an RBI double in the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Reds took the series finale, 5–2, scoring three runs in the bottom of the eighth to pull ahead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On August 1, the Dodgers began a three-game series at George M.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Steinbrenner Field against the Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the opener, Clayton Kershaw pitched six shutout innings while Freddie Freeman had a double, a home run, and drove in three runs in the 5–0 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Blake Snell, in his first start since going on the injured list in April, had eight strikeouts in five innings but allowed three runs (two home runs to Yandy Díaz) and the Dodgers lost 4–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers finished the series with another shutout win, 3–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman and Andy Pages each drove in a run and Mookie Betts hit a sacrifice fly while Yoshinobu Yamamoto struck out six in 5+2⁄3 scoreless innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Louis Cardinals visited Dodger Stadium for a three-game series starting on August 4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The opener was tied 2–2 at the top of the ninth, and Brock Stewart allowed the game-winning run, an RBI hit to Yohel Pozo, leading to a 3–2 defeat.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, Max Muncy had four hits, including two home runs and Teoscar Hernández had three hits, also including two home runs, and the Dodgers won 12–6.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was Muncy's 19th career multi-homer game for the Dodgers, tying Mike Piazza for the most since the team moved to Los Angeles.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the series, Shohei Ohtani struck out eight batters in four innings as the starting pitcher and also hit a two run home run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Cardinals won 5–3 after Alex Freeland allowed two runs at the top of the eighth on a throwing error.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next series was against the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the opener, Kershaw allowed one run on seven hits and Betts hit a two-run home run in the bottom of the fifth, leading to a 5–2 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Snell had another excellent performance, striking out 10 in five, and Ohtani reached 40 home runs for the third consecutive season and fourth overall.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] He was also only the fourth Dodgers player in history with multiple such seasons (Duke Snider, Gil Hodges and Shawn Green).
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers took a 3–1 lead in the series finale thanks to home runs by Ohtani and Freeman.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Back-to-back home runs by Vladimir Guerrero Jr. and Addison Barger in the eighth and a solo homer by Ernie Clement in the top of the ninth had the Blue Jays up.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers managed to load the bases in the bottom of the inning with Ohtani and Betts due up but were unable to score and the Blue Jays won 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was the first game since the 1982 season that the Dodgers had at least 10 hits and 10 walks and lost.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] They were 1 for 10 with runners in scoring position and left 16 runners on base.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Next up was a brief three-game road trip against the Los Angeles Angels at Angel Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Yamamoto struggled in the first game, allowing six runs in only 4+2⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers made it close by scoring four runs in the eighth on a solo homer by Ohtani and a three-run homer by Muncy, but lost 7–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, Dalton Rushing and Ohtani hit home runs, but the bullpen faltered and the Angels won, 7–6, on a walk-off RBI hit from Jo Adell in the 10th inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Angels finished the season sweep with a 6–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers tied the game on a four-ball walk to Will Smith but Justin Wrobleski blew the save after allowing a two-run hit to Logan O'Hoppe.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] With the loss, the Dodgers fell out of first place in the division for the first time since April 27.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On July 15, the division leading San Diego Padres came to Los Angeles for a three-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Kershaw allowed only one run on two hits and one walk in six innings, Teoscar Hernández homered and the Dodgers picked up a 3–2 victory to even the division race.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Snell pitched six shutout innings, Hernández hit another home run and sacrifice fly while a Jackson Merrill fielding error allowed two more runs to score as the Dodgers won, 6–0, and retook the lead in the NL West.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers scored four runs in the first inning of the series finale with home runs by Freeman and Pages.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Padres came back to tie the game but Betts hit a go-ahead home run in the eighth as the Dodgers swept the series with a 5–4 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers next left for a seven-game road trip, beginning with a four-game series against the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Two fielding mistakes by Teoscar Hernández in right field led to two Rockies runs and they walked off the Dodgers, 4–3 to open the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the following game, Alex Call had four hits (including a home run), scored three runs and drove in two as the Dodgers won 11–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Hernández homered again, but Ohtani struggled in his next start, giving up nine hits and allowing five runs in four innings, and the Dodgers were defeated, 8–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers wound up splitting the series with a 9–5 victory in the finale.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman and Pages homered and Alex Freeland had three hits, including a double and triple, in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The battle between the top two teams in the division resumed when the Dodgers visited Petco Park on August 22 to resume their rivalry with the Padres.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Snell began the series by allowing two runs in seven innings, however the Dodgers could only manage one hit against Yu Darvish in six innings and three overall as they lost 2–1 and fell back into a tie for the division lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Padres took over the division lead with a 5–1 win the next day.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers managed only two hits against Nestor Cortes and three relievers, with a solo home run by Freeland one of them.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game between the two teams in the regular season, the Dodgers won 8–2 to even the division race.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] They hit four home runs, including two by Freeman and a three-run homer by Rushing.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On July 25, the Dodgers hosted the Cincinnati Reds for a three-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Pages hit two home runs with three RBI, two more runs scored on a Reds error and Betts also homered as the Dodgers won the opener, 7–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Emmet Sheehan struckout 10 in seven innings while only allowing two hits and one walk.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game, Kershaw allowed only two hits and one run with six strikeouts in five innings while Ohtani and Miguel Rojas drove in runs, Smith homered and the Dodgers won 6–3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Kiké Hernández and Rushing each had two RBIs while Rushing homered and the Dodgers swept the series with a 5–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani earned his first win as a Dodger, throwing nine strikeouts and allowing one run (a solo home run to Noelvi Marte) in five innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers pitching staff struck out 19 batters in the game, a franchise record.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Arizona Diamondbacks came to town next.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Snell struckout eight in 5+1⁄3 innings, but the offense struggled, only managing to get three hits against Diamondbacks starter Zac Gallen and three relivers in a 3–0 loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] A fielding error from Pages lead to one run scoring and Kirby Yates allowed a three-run home run to Ildemaro Vargas at the top of the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, Yamamoto struck out 10 batters while allowing only four hits and one run in seven innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Corbin Carroll hit a three-run home run in the eighth inning for the Diamondbacks to tie the game, but the Dodgers won 5–4 on a walk-off home run by Smith.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers went back on the road on September 2 to play the Pittsburgh Pirates at PNC Park.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Shohei Ohtani had three hits, including his 100th home run as a Dodger and two doubles, but the Pirates won the game 9–7.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Pirates shut out the Dodgers 3–0 the following day.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Pirates finished off a series sweep with a 5–3 victory in the finale.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Paul Skenes allowed only two hits and one walk with eight strikeouts in six shutout innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Next they traveled to Oriole Park at Camden Yards to play the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freddie Freeman hit a solo home run but Samuel Basallo's walk-off home run gave the Orioles a 2–1 win and sent the Dodgers to the fourth straight loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The following day, Yoshinobu Yamamoto struck out 10 batters and took a no-hitter through 8+2⁄3 innings before Jackson Holliday's home run ended his day with an MLB career high 112 pitches.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Blake Treinen came in out of the bullpen, loaded the bases and walked in a run before Emmanuel Rivera drove in two on a single off Tanner Scott and the Orioles won 4–3 to extend the Dodgers losing streak.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The road trip and the losing streak came to an end the next day, with a 5–2 Dodgers win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Clayton Kershaw allowed two runs in 5+2⁄3 innings while striking out eight.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani hit two home runs and Mookie Betts added one as well.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On September 8, the Colorado Rockies came to Dodger Stadium for a three-game series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Tyler Glasnow struck out 11 batters in seven innings without allowing a hit and the Dodgers lost a chance at a combined no-hitter in the ninth when Scott allowed a leadoff single to Ryan Ritter.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Betts and Freeman drove in the Dodgers' only runs in a 3–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, the Dodgers hit four home runs, two of which came from Teoscar Hernández, for a 7–2 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Emmet Sheehan had nine strikeouts and gave up only three hits in seven innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers finished off a sweep of the Rockies with a 9–0 shutout win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Blake Snell allowed only two hits and two walks while striking out 11 in six innings while Betts had four hits and five RBI in the game, including a grand slam in the eighth inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers traveled to Oracle Park to face the San Francisco Giants starting on September 12.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the series opener, Yamamoto struck out 10 in seven innings while allowing only one hit and Michael Conforto hit a solo home run in the seventh, but Scott blew another game, allowing a grand slam to Patrick Bailey in the bottom of the tenth, resulting in a 5–1 loss.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Teoscar Hernández had two doubles and drove in three runs, Ohtani had three hits, including a home run, and the Dodgers won 13–7.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers took the series finale with a 10–2 rout of the Giants.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Tyler Glasnow allowed three hits and one run in 6+2⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Teoscar Hernández had four hits and Betts and Freeman each had three.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani set a new Dodgers record with his 135th run scored of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers returned home on September 15 to play the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Sheehan followed opener Anthony Banda (who allowed a solo home run to Kyle Schwarber) and pitched 5+2⁄3 and did not allow a hit until a Otto Kemp double in the seventh.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Jack Dreyer replaced him and allowed a three-run homer to Weston Wilson which gave the Phillies their first lead after the Dodgers had led 4–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] After alternating home runs by Betts, Bryce Harper, and Andy Pages, the score was tied at five after regulation.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, Treinen allowed a double steal, followed by a sacrifice fly to J.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Realmuto in the tenth, and the Dodgers lost 6–5.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game, Kiké Hernández had three RBI and Ohtani homered and pitched five scoreless, no-hit innings, becoming the first player in Dodgers history to record 50 home runs and 50 strikeouts in a single season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Phillies scored six runs in the sixth inning, three of them on a Brandon Marsh homer.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Treinen struggled again, allowing a three-run home run to Rafael Marchán in the ninth for a 9–6 defeat.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Freeman and Ohtani homered and Snell struck out 12 and only gave up two hits in seven innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The final home series of the season was four-games against the Giants, starting on September 18.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers, as a team, struck out 14 batters, while walking 10, and only allowed one hit, in a 2–1 win to start it off.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The next day, Kershaw, who announced that he would retire at the end of the season, made the final regular season home start of his career, striking out six in 4+1⁄3 innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Miguel Rojas homered in the fourth and Ohtani and Betts hit back-to-back home runs in the fifth as the Dodgers won, 6–3, clinching their 13th straight postseason appearance (tying the 1995–2007 New York Yankees for second most all time).
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers hit four home runs in the third game of the series, a 7–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] However, the Dodgers were unable to sweep the series, losing the finale 3–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Sheehan pitched seven scoreless innings, striking out 10 while giving up only one hit.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Giants scored three runs in the eighth off Treinen and that was all they needed.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] On September 23, the Dodgers began a six-game road trip to close out the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The first series was against the Arizona Diamondbacks at Chase Field.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Ohtani struck out eight batters in six shutout innings, while Teoscar Hernández and Ben Rortvedt each homered, but the bullpen's struggles continued.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Diamondbacks scored three runs in the seventh inning and then Scott allowed two in the ninth, including a sacrifice fly to Geraldo Perdomo to walk off the Dodgers, 5–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] It was Scott's 10th blown save of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the second game of the series, Snell allowed one run in six innings, Pages homered in the fourth, and the Dodgers jumped out to another early lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The bullpen again blew the lead, allowing the Diamondbacks to score three runs in the eighth to tie it.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] The Dodgers managed to win this game, 5–4, thanks to an RBI hit by Tommy Edman in the 11th inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the finale, Yamamoto struck out seven in six scoreless innings, the Dodgers hit four home runs (including two by Freeman) and they won 8–0.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] With the win, the Dodgers clinched their 4th consecutive National League West title and the 12th in 13 seasons.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Next, the Dodgers traveled to T-Mobile Park to play the Seattle Mariners in the final series of the season.The Dodgers won the first game of the series, 3–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] Kiké Hernández hit a two-run home run in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the next game, he had another three hits and two RBI while Rushing also homered in a 5–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p04] In the final game of the regular season, Kershaw pitched 5+1⁄3 scoreless innings with seven strikeouts in his final MLB start, Ohtani broke his own franchise record with his 55th homerun and the Dodgers finished off a sweep of the Mariners with a 6–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] After finishing with the National League West title and the third seed in the playoffs, the Dodgers played the Cincinnati Reds in the Wild Card Series at Dodger Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Blake Snell started the first game of the series for the Dodgers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] He struck out nine batters in seven innings, while allowing four hits, two walks, and two runs (both in the seventh).
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Shohei Ohtani and Teoscar Hernández both homered twice in the game and Tommy Edman also homered in the 10–5 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The five home runs by the Dodgers in the game matched a franchise post-season record set previously in Game 5 of the 2021 NLCS and Game 3 of the 2020 NLCS.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The 2021 game was also the only other time the Dodgers had two teammates each hit two home runs in a post-season game (Chris Taylor and A.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the second game of the series, Yoshinobu Yamamoto struck out nine in 6+1⁄3 innings while allowing only two unearned runs.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Mookie Betts had four hits, including three doubles, as the Dodgers won 8–4 to sweep the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers faced the Philadelphia Phillies in the division series starting at Citizens Bank Park.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the opening game, the Phillies took an early 3–0 lead on a two-run triple by J.T.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Realmuto and a sacrifice fly in the second.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Shohei Ohtani pitched six innings, allowing only three runs while striking out nine.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] A two-run double by Kiké Hernández in the sixth and a three-run Teoscar Hernández home run the following inning gave the Dodgers a 5–3 lead, and they held on to win by that score with Roki Sasaki picking up his first professional save.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The second game was a scoreless pitching duel through six innings as Blake Snell gave up only one hit and struck out nine while Jesús Luzardo matched him with a scoreless six.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] However, the Dodgers got to him in the seventh, scoring four runs, two on an RBI single by Will Smith.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Phillies came back, with one run in the eighth and then two in the ninth off Blake Treinen before Sasaki came in to retire the final batter with the tying run on third for a 4–3 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The series moved to Dodger Stadium for Game 3 but Yoshinobu Yamamoto struggled for the Dodgers, pitching only four innings and allowing three runs, including a home run by Kyle Schwarber.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Schwarber hit a second home run, in the eighth off Clayton Kershaw as the Phillies scored five runs that inning to break open the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers meanwhile were only able to get one run (a solo home run by Tommy Edman) off starter Aaron Nola and Ranger Suárez, who worked five innings of relief to collect the win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Phillies won 8–2 to prevent the series sweep.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The following game was a pitchers duel between Tyler Glasnow (eight strikeouts in six scoreless innings) and Cristopher Sánchez (five strikeouts in 6+1⁄3).
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Both teams scored a run in the seventh and then the game stayed 1–1 into extra innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers won the game when pinch runner Hyeseong Kim scored on a throwing error by Phillies reliever Orion Kerkering in the 11th inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The 2–1 win clinched the series for the Dodgers.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers advanced to their second straight National League Championship Series, facing the Milwaukee Brewers, starting at American Family Field.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the opener, Blake Snell allowed only one hit while striking out 10 batters in eight innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers scored on a solo home run by Freddie Freeman in the sixth and a bases-loaded walk by Mookie Betts in the ninth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Brewers got a run in the bottom of the ninth and then Blake Treinen struck out Brice Turang with the bases loaded for the Dodgers' 2–1 win.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Jackson Chourio led off the second game with a solo home run on the first pitch thrown by Yoshinobu Yamamoto, but Yamamoto settled down after that.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] He only allowed the one run on three hits and one walk while striking out seven in a complete game victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Teoscar Hernández and Max Muncy homered for the Dodgers, who won 5–1 to win the second game of the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The series moved to Dodger Stadium for the third game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Tyler Glasnow struck out eight in 5+2⁄3 innings while allowing one run on three hits and three walks.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Shohei Ohtani led off the game with a triple off Brewers' opener Aaron Ashby and then Betts drove him in with a double.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Jacob Misiorowski struck out nine in five innings for the Brewers, but the Dodgers got two runs in the sixth on an RBI single by Tommy Edman and a throwing error by reliever Abner Uribe.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The bullpens didn't allow any more runs, and the Dodgers moved to within one game of a series sweep with a 3–1 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the next game, Ohtani started on the mound and pitched six scoreless innings with only two hits and three walks while striking out 10 batters.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] He also hit three home runs in the Dodgers 5–1 victory, winning the NLCS Most Valuable Player Award and sending the Dodgers to their second straight NL title.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers appeared in the World Series for the second straight year and the third time in the last six years.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] They faced the Toronto Blue Jays, the top seed in the American League.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The series began at Rogers Centre as a result of the Blue Jays having one more win than the Dodgers during the regular season.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the opener, the Dodgers took an early 2–0 lead only for the Blue Jays to tie it up in the fourth on a two-run Daulton Varsho home run and then erupt for nine runs in the sixth.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] A pinch-hit grand slam by Addison Barger and a two-run homer by Alejandro Kirk were the key blows in that inning.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Blake Snell struggled, allowing five runs on eight hits and three walks, in his five-plus innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Shohei Ohtani hit a two-run home run in the seventh, but the Dodgers lost the game, 11–4.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In the second game, Yoshinobu Yamamoto allowed only one run on four hits with no walks and eight strikeouts in a complete game, 5–1 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Max Muncy and Will Smith each homered in the seventh inning, and Smith drove in three of the five runs in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Yamamoto was the first pitcher to throw multiple complete games in the same postseason since Madison Bumgarner in 2014 and the first to do it in back-to-back games since Curt Schilling in 2001.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The series returned to Dodger Stadium for Game 3.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Tyler Glasnow pitched 4+2⁄3 innings, allowing four runs (two earned) on five hits, and three walks.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Teoscar Hernández homered in the second and had four hits in the game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Ohtani also had four hits, including two home runs and two doubles.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The game went into extra innings tied at five and wound up going 18 innings before Freddie Freeman won it on a walk-off home run.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Ohtani was intentionally walked four times in the game, a World Series record, and his nine times reaching base in the game was also a record.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The 18 innings tied the World Series record, previously set by Game 3 of the 2018 World Series, also played at Dodger Stadium.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] However, the Blue Jays evened up the series again the next day with a 6–2 victory.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] A two-run home run by Vladimir Guerrero Jr. in the third off Ohtani and a four-run seventh were all they needed.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Ohtani allowed four runs in six innings while striking out twice in three at-bats.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In their final home game of the season, the Dodgers lost Game 5, 6–1.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Davis Schneider and Guerrero homered back-to-back off Snell to start the game, and the Dodgers never recovered.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Trey Yesavage struck out 12 and only gave up three hits and one run (a solo homer by Kiké Hernández) in seven innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Yamamoto pitched again in Game 6 back in Toronto, allowing one run on five hits with six strikeouts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers got three runs in the third inning on an RBI double by Smith and then a two-run single by Mookie Betts.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Glasnow came in for the ninth inning with the tying runs on second and third and managed to get out of the threat to preserve the 3–1 win and send the series to a seventh game.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] In Game 7, Ohtani started and gave up a three-run home run to Bo Bichette in the third inning to give the Blue Jays the early lead.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Dodgers scratched back with two runs on sacrifice flies in the fourth and sixth by Teoscar Hernández and Tommy Edman respectively.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] The Blue Jays got one more in the bottom of the sixth on a go-ahead RBI double by Andres Gimenez to extend the lead to 4–2.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Max Muncy homered in the eighth and Miguel Rojas in the ninth to tie it up and send the game to extra innings.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Yamamoto pitched 2+2⁄3 innings one day after his Game 6 start.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Will Smith hit a solo home run in the 11th inning to put the Dodgers ahead, and then after Guerrero doubled to lead off the bottom of the inning, the Dodgers turned a game and series-winning double play.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Yamamoto was named the World Series Most Valuable Player Award after winning three games in the series.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Yamamoto became the first pitcher to win three World Series games since Randy Johnson did it in 2001.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] After the 2024 season, the Oklahoma City AAA franchise changed its name and branding to the Oklahoma City Comets, an homage to Oklahoma native Mickey Mantle's nickname, "the Commerce Comet", and to honor the city's ties to the aerospace industry.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] Their first round pick was dropped 10 spots by virtue of them surpassing the third luxury tax threshold.
[src:ace-baseball/2025-los-angeles-dodgers-season-p05] They also gained a competitive balance pick between the first and second rounds as part of their trading Gavin Lux to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] In baseball, an **ace** is a starting pitcher considered the best pitcher on a team's starting rotation.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] Barring injury or exceptional circumstances, a team's ace typically starts on Opening Day.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] In addition, aces are usually preferred to start crucial playoff games, sometimes on three days' rest.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] The term may be a derivation of the nickname of Asa Brainard (real first name: "Asahel"), a 19th-century star pitcher, who was sometimes referred to as "Ace".
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] In the early days of baseball, the term *ace* was used to refer to a run.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] Modern baseball analysts and fans have started using the term *ace* to refer to the elite pitchers in the game, not necessarily to the best starting pitcher on each team.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-baseball] For example, the April 27, 1981, *Sports Illustrated* cover was captioned "The Amazing A's and Their Five Aces" to describe the starting rotation of the 1981 Oakland Athletics, which featured Mike Norris, Rick Langford, Matt Keough, Steve McCatty, and Brian Kingman.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Over the years, the Toronto Blue Jays have created three full-time mascots, all of which portray the bird for which the team was named.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] BJ Birdy and Diamond returned in 2026 for the team's fitieth season, alongside Domer, appearing Sundays.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] BJ Birdy was revived without copyright permission from his creator Kevin Shanahan, who maintained full ownership of the character during and after its run.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Kevin Shanahan was an employee of Ontario Place, a theme park attraction run by the provincial government of Ontario, located on Toronto's lakeshore across from municipally-run Exhibition Place, site of Exhibition Stadium, the team's home field at the time.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] As a University of Toronto student, Shanahan designed and performed in a moose costume at the park, to replace the more "motley-looking thing" they already had.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The second moose costume was uncomfortable, so he designed a more comfortable bird costume.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] A friend suggested to him the Blue Jays might want a mascot.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Not a baseball fan, he had never seen a live game.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He commented "it didn't take me long to see why a mascot was needed.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Otherwise your mind wanders." Shanahan was a part-time science student, before he later dropped out.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Previously he had attended Michael Power High school, where he drew comics for the school newspaper.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The team was working on a deal with CHUM Limited to develop a mascot character, after the Montreal Expos had added the character of Youppi! earlier in the year.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] In 1985, the BJ Birdy character was described as "lovable, irascible, curious, impudent, mischievous, and often the victim of his own impulsiveness." Much of the routines were improvised.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He'll duck behind a dugout and then pop up again.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He does what a lot of fans would do if they weren't so reserved." The costume had "perfect vision", and was said to be quite agile.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] During the 1981 Major League Baseball strike, 22-year-old Shanahan told the *Star* that he would lose $7000 if the whole season was cancelled.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He suggested he might return to Ontario Place, but worried the strike might permanently kill the character.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] During the strike, he rebuilt his Basil Beaver and Mickey Moose costume heads for Ontario Place, and received a contract to build six more animals in the autumn.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] By the end of the strike, he estimated a loss of $3600.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The character and its actor had a continuously strained relationship with the team and some fans.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] When receiving complaints from the fans or media on his behavior at a game, the team front office would apparently reply "B.J.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Who?" In 1985, he commented: "I'm always walking a fine wire.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] I found out early that Blue Jays won't back me up, that I'm on my own.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] On April 1, 1985, the first *BJ Birdy* comic ran in the *Toronto Star*, created by Shanahan.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] In a preview article, he commented on the character: "I see him as an underbird but he'll definitely be his own bird.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He'll get the odd quip in his favor, he'll second-guess like fans do but, most of the time, everything will fall back on him.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Of course, he might develop into something totally different.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] I have ideas but that isn't to say they and B.J. won't change.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Situations that B.J. got into at the stadium were limited but this way the sky's the limit.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He can fall off stadiums, go through walls, do silly, little things.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] There's total freedom." The character often criticized Jays management.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The *Globe* noted that fans "had grown abusive.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Broadcasters question the reason for his existence.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The team's front office offers only middling support." The newspaper noted a negative bent to the comic, with many strips taking shots at those groups.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] When Paul Beeston was asked about his opinion on a strip centering on him, vice president he commented "What comic strip?
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] I didn't know he had one." In another strip, BJ Birdy's mother is about to hit mascot-hating broadcaster Tony Kubek on the head.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The comic ran in the sports section of the Toronto Star (during baseball season only) for about three and a half years; later strips were presented under the title *BJ Birdy's Bush League*.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Despite — or perhaps because of — its occasionally controversial nature, the comic was not especially successful, and wound down at the conclusion of the 1988 season.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] On the move to SkyDome, "BJ Birdy" told the *Star* that the team should keep prices as is.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] BJ Birdy gained wider notoriety on May 22, 1993, when he was ejected from a Blue Jays game against the Minnesota Twins for trying to influence an umpire's call on a caught line drive.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] In the bottom of the first inning, umpire Jim McKean ruled that Twins infielder David McCarty didn't catch a line drive hit by Roberto Alomar, ruling the play a hit.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Although the ruling favoured his team, BJ Birdy was caught up in the excitement of the play and attempted to get the crowd to make the "hit" ruling just as McKean was actually making the ruling.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] McKean still took exception to the antic, ejecting BJ Birdy from the game, which the Jays still won 7–0.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Over the character's final seasons, Shanahan suggested that Jays management turned down multiple appearance requests for BJ Birdy.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The Raptor, mascot of the Toronto Raptors basketball team, was meanwhile gaining acclaim for his acrobatic routines.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The Jays noted the admiration for the NBA team's "total entertainment package".
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The team had its second lowest opening day attendance in 1999, desperately trying to attract audiences.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The *Star* commented that the team's desperation was evident, suggesting that "the nadir probably reached when a van circled the field pulling a flatbed which bore B.J.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Birdy, a massive plastic rodent, two dancing bears and a man firing T-shirts into the stands with a bazooka." Shanahan retained ownership of the character, despite initial attempts to sell the rights and costume to the club.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Shanahan was called into a meeting with the senior vice-president of marketing for the Toronto Blue Jays, Terry Zuk; the two apparently had not met before.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He was told he was being replaced by two new mascots.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Shanahan again offered to sell the costume and copyrights, but the club declined.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The team suggested, if it were too hard to hold onto the costume, the Jays Care Foundation would gladly accept a donation; he flatly refused.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] It was also suggested Shanahan might be interested in training the new performers.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Seeking legal advice, he informed the club the new mascots could not debut before his contract expired on December 31, well after the season's end.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] In early December, the story about BJ Birdy's two replacements made the news.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Shanahan commented that "there's not a great deal of pain in this.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] But it bothers me that the Jays talked about it before my contract was up.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] They gave their word they'd wait until December 31." General Manager Gord Ash contested that "there was no intent to reveal that.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] BJ Birdy returned for Sunday games in April 2026, appearing with Diamond and SkyDome mascot Domer, as part of the team's fiftieth anniversary.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He also appeared at at least one weekday game.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] It wasn't until CBC News reporter Haydn Watters contacted Shanahan for comment that he, as the copyright holder, was aware of the reboot.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The new costume was created without permission.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] As of early May 2026, Shanahan still hadn't heard from the team, and *Toronto Star* didn't receive a response to their request for comment.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Quickly, some in the sports media asked "Double the pleasure?
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Or, double the pain?" News of a naming contest led to suggestions like Swing and A Miss, More and Annoying, and Bird and Brain.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] As of early December 1999, four people expressed interest in applying, three of them from the United States.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] By the first round of auditions on January 10, 2000, the club had received about 70 applications.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The characters themselves were conceived and designed by Kelly Giannopoulos and Diane Semark.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] "We looked for the most interesting personality traits and then actually gave the mascots a past, a sort of legend that went with their story." The duo were designed with distinct plumage and faces, to reflect their gender.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Sugar's Costume Studio built the outfits based on their designs.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Their personality traits were modelled after Jim Carrey and Goldie Hawn, because "both of them have a wild and zany side." Their original names were Slider and Curveball.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] On March 4, 2000, two new names were unveiled through the Toronto Blue Jays "Name the Mascots Contest" ACE and DIAMOND.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Winner of contest: Toronto High School Student A.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] The costumes were built by Sugar's Mascot Costumes in Toronto.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] An early article suggested they would wear varied clothes; "tuxedos for formal events and surgical garb for hospital visits." The new costumes were lightweight and featured athletic pants to allow for stunts.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Brennan Anderson played Ace for five years, bringing his competitive gymnastics and media background.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] He later became a sales manager at Sugar's.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Diamond performers included then-Ryerson University student Angelina Milanovic, University of Toronto musical theatre student Larissa Bathgate, and Amanda Barker.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Ace became sole mascot of the Blue Jays in 2004, after the team removed Diamond before the season opened.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] She returned in 2026, for Sunday games during the team's 50th season.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] A second blue jay mascot, named Junior, is present on "Junior Jays days", usually Saturdays home games, when children are invited to run the bases after the games.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Affiliate team the Dunedin Blue Jays are represented by DJay the Blue Jay; he was named BJ in 1998.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Ace's official website jokingly mentioned that his father invented bird stickers commonly found on windows and his mother was a goose feather supplier.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] In 2012, Ace underwent some changes when the team changed their logo and uniforms.
[src:ace-baseball/ace-mascot] Ace was given more fur and his beak was changed from gray to blue and the bottom of his legs were switched from black to gray.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Born about 1841 in Albany, New York, Brainard played outfield and second base for the mighty Excelsiors of Brooklyn in 1860.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Led by the sensational teenage fast pitcher, Jim Creighton, the team toured New York state from Albany to Buffalo, a major event in the baseball boom.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] The Civil War curtailed that; after playing 21 matches in 1860, the Excelsiors played none in 1861 and only a few in 1862.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Following Creighton's premature death, Brainard succeeded him as the regular pitcher and remained in that role for four seasons.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] The Excelsiors played a heavy schedule again in 1866, the first full peacetime season, winning 13 of 20 games—a strong team but no longer a threat to the strongest.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Young Candy Cummings, one inventor of the curveball, evidently won the pitcher's job by the end of the season.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Creighton biographer Thomas Gilbert points out that three of the preeminent pitchers of the amateur era, Creighton, Brainard, and Cummings, were each mentored and caught by one man, Excelsior veteran catcher Joseph "Joe" Leggett.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] In 1867 the National club of Washington completed the first western tour, playing ten games from Ohio to Missouri during three weeks in July.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Brainard probably joined the team in the fall, in time for a shorter tour from Troy, New York to Philadelphia, where the strongest teams were based.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] At 27 years old, he moved to Cincinnati for the 1868 season where he shared second base and pitcher with manager Harry Wright.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Open professionalism was one year away but the long move suggests that Brainard was somehow compensated by club members if not by the club.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Cincinnati fielded a strong team that year, with five of the famous team already in place.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] When the NABBP permitted professionalism, the Red Stockings hired five incumbents including Brainard and five new men to complete its famous Nine, the first team on salary for a season.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] In their 1869 campaign, Asa Brainard pitched more than 70% of the innings, Harry Wright more than 25%, as the team toured the continent undefeated, vanquishing all of the plausible challengers.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] With Charlie Sweasy ensconced at second, the two pitchers now shared center field.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] The Red Stockings toured again in 1870, with Brainard pitching almost 70% of the innings in 74 games.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Occasionally beaten this year, the team may have been the strongest again, but the club dropped professional baseball in the fall.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Harry Wright was hired to organize a new team in Boston, where he signed three teammates for 1871, also bringing along the "Red Stockings" designation.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] The other five regulars including Asa Brainard and catcher Doug Allison signed with Nick Young's Washington Olympics, an established club that also joined the new, entirely professional National Association (NA).
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] The five former Red Stockings led the Olympics to a respectable finish in the inaugural NA season.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Brainard's published "career statistics" begin with this year.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Later, Brainard played from 1871 to 1874 for the Washington Olympics, Middletown Mansfields, and Baltimore Canaries, all teams in the National Association.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Brainard died of pneumonia in Denver, Colorado at age 47, only a few months after John Bass at age 40, the first major league ballplayer to die in that city.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] Owing to its dry climate and relative convenience, Denver had become a destination for people suffering from tuberculosis.
[src:ace-baseball/asa-brainard] He is buried in Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn.
